# WHY SEPARATE .ENV FILES?
# -------------------------
# 1. Backend uses Node.js dotenv - reads from backend/.env
# 2. React only reads variables prefixed with REACT_APP_ from frontend/.env
# 3. Each environment has different variable names and purposes
# 4. Keeps concerns separated and configuration clearer

# ================================
# QUICK START INSTRUCTIONS
# ================================
#
# 1. Copy backend/.env.example to backend/.env
#    Windows: copy backend\.env.example backend\.env
#    Linux/Mac: cp backend/.env.example backend/.env
#
# 2. Copy frontend/.env.example to frontend/.env
#    Windows: copy frontend\.env.example frontend\.env
#    Linux/Mac: cp frontend/.env.example frontend/.env
#
# 3. Fill in your actual values in both .env files
#
# 4. See SETUP_GUIDE.md for detailed setup instructions
#
# ================================

# BACKEND VARIABLES (go in backend/.env)
# =======================================

# MONGO_URI - MongoDB connection string
# JWT_SECRET - Secret key for JWT token signing (min 32 chars)
# EMAIL - Gmail address for sending emails
# APP_PASSWORD - Gmail app password (16 characters, no spaces)
# NAME - Sender name for emails
# CLIENT_ID - Google OAuth Client ID
# REACT_APP_FRONTEND_URL - Frontend URL for CORS (http://localhost:3000)
# REACT_APP_BACKEND_URL - Backend URL (http://localhost:5000)

# FRONTEND VARIABLES (go in frontend/.env)
# =========================================
# REACT_APP_BACKEND_URL - Backend API URL (http://localhost:5000)
# REACT_APP_GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID - Google OAuth Client ID (same as CLIENT_ID above)

